th cold ethereal light. Her weapons are twin revolvers of legendary power. Wraith is a revolver of polished silver, its barrel etched with the names of the dead she has laid to rest, firing ghostly soul projectiles that pass through flesh to strike at the spirit itself—the souls scream as they fly, a sound that chills the blood of the living and terrifies the undead. Starfire is a revolver of deep royal purple, its surface inlaid with veins of gold that glow with inner light, firing concentrated beams of laser energy that can cut through steel and stone. Together, the two revolvers grant her unlimited ammunition—for the dead are never truly gone, and the light of the Dark West never fully fades. This shadow bounty hunter was the daughter of a legendary bounty hunter, born in a dusty town called Redemption's End in the Dark West, taught to shoot before she could read. Her brother Clint was her shadow, always following her, always trying to match her shots. When a gang of revenants—undead gunslingers bound to a demon lord—rode into town and killed their father, Shiela swore to hunt every revenant, every demon, every soul that preyed on the innocent. But Clint grew tired of the endless hunt and made a deal with the same demon lord, trading his soul for power. Shiela found him standing over the bodies of a family they had been hired to protect, his eyes no longer human, and she could not pull the trigger. The spirits of departed bounty hunters found her in the desert, half-dead from thirst and grief, and offered her a pact: her service in exchange for power that no mortal gunslinger had ever possessed. She accepted, and the spirits poured into her, filling her with their memories, their skills, their cold undying purpose. Now she rides through the Dark West—a lawless expanse of dusty plains, rocky mesas, and ghost towns where the sun bleaches bones and the wind carries whispers of forgotten sins. A tumbleweed rolls across a deserted main street, the only light the flick